<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Start your letter from this line so you have room for the ATL logo/address…</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-align:right; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SCP0003</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by ATL</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ATL, the education union, is an independent, registered trade union and professional association, representing approximately 160,000 teachers, head teachers, lecturers and support staff in maintained and independent nurseries, schools, sixth form, tertiary and further education colleges in the United Kingdom. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AMiE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is the trade union and professional association for leaders and managers in colleges and schools, and is a distinct section of ATL. We recognise the link between education policy and members' conditions of service.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ATL wishes to highlight the following issues to the Select Committee:-</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.41pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the national increase in pupil numbers is having a disproportionate effect in some areas of the country; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.41pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the impact of government policy on restricting local planning for school places in favour of free schools and academies is preventing resources from reaching the areas in most need; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.41pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the religious nature of many free schools makes them unattractive to some parents; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.41pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the government’s policy on teacher training is leading to a potential crisis in teacher numbers; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.41pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> impact on school places of changes to the school participation age.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Limits on Local Authority Schools</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ONS statistics put the number of live births for 2012 at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">729,674, the highest since 1971.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The ONS project that all regions of England will see an increase in their primary aged population by 2015.  This ranges from around 10 per cent in the South West, North West and North East to 15 per cent in London.</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  These are based on the assumption that net migration is zero.  However, individual communities and boroughs are facing greater challenges; Barking and Dagenham has seen a 50% rise in the number of under-four year olds since 2001.</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  With such wide national fluctuations it is essential that decisions on school places are taken locally.    </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, legislation states that if a local authority thinks that there is a need for an additional school in their area ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they must seek proposals for the establishment of an Academy’.</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  This clause effectively ends the local democratic process in the provision of school places in England.  Coventry City Council recently scrapped plans for two new primary schools, part funded by the developers of new housing provision, when it was made clear that permission would only by granted for the schools if they were outside of the council’s control.</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  It is unfortunate that Coventry have turned down two new schools when other parts of the country there is an unseemly scramble to create additional places in any disused building available, resulting in the government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">relaxing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> planning legislation for schools.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A freedom of information request by the Guardian has revealed that 25% of free schools designate themselves as faith schools.  This figure is likely to be higher as a free school may have a faith ethos but not be designated a faith school.  With no local democratic involvement in the decision making process for free schools there is no guarantee that the new schools will reflect the community.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wandsworth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, for example, has only 1,600 Jewish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">constituents but permission was given for a Jewish primary free school.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Research undertaken by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">YouGov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for Lancaster University showed that less than a quarter of people surveyed would be likely to send their child to a faith school and almost half did not support government funding of faith schools.</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[vi]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Teacher shortage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ATL believes that in addition to the shortage of school places the government is sleepwalking into a shortage of qualified teachers.  As highlighted in her Guardian article, the former Secretary of State for Education, Estelle Morris, </span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[vii]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Predictions show that there will be a need for an extra 300,000 places in state-funded nursery and primary schools by 2015, with an additional 680,000 places needed by the end of the decade.</span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[viii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  These places will need an increase to the teaching workforce of at least 23,000 teachers and corresponding increases in school leadership teams.  There are already difficulties in recruiting and retaining sufficient head teachers.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There have been calls from some local authorities for a relaxation on the limits of pupils in the classroom.  According to the government, the average class for five- to seven-year-olds now contains 27.3 pupils, up from 26.9 in 2011 and just 25.7 in 2008.  At the same time, 47,290 (3.1%) of pupils are being taught in lessons of 31 or more children up from 43,065 a year ago and just 24,760 in 2008.</span><a name="_ednref9"></a><a href="#_edn9">[ix]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   ATL believes that, in addition to the adverse impact that this has on the educational attainment of pupils, the stresses and demands on teachers are increased.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The BBC has reported that schools are looking at radical changes to the existing schooling model to cope with the increase in numbers, including running in the school in shifts.</span><a name="_ednref10"></a><a href="#_edn10">[x]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  ATL is concerned that these models are being considered.  ATL already recognises the difficulties faced by families with children at different schools with different term dates and conflicting school start and end times.  The effect on working families if these shift arrangements were to be introduced would be immense.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Other government proposals may be compromised by the shortage in pupil places.  At the same time as we are seeing an increase in pupil numbers, two year olds are becoming eligible for school places and the leaving age is being raised to 18.  We are also concerned at the effect that this would have on the government’s proposals for wrap-round childcare centred on schools.  To be successful, the government’s wish for parents to have choice as to which school to send their child to means that there must be a surplus of places to allow choice.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.29pt; padding-left:8.06pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ATL strongly believes that the government must use the information available to ascertain the number of school places and teachers needed in the near future and ensure that investment is available to meet these needs.  Government needs control over the supply of teachers and the School Direct programme is reducing their influence over the numbers of trainee teachers.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local authorities need the powers to make decisions locally to ensure that the right number and type of places are available.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">National Pupil Projections: Future Trends in Pupil Numbers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, OSR 02/2012, 24 January 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> BBC, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">London council considers opening schools in split shifts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, BBC website, 4 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn3"></a><a href="#_ednref3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Education Act 2011, Schedule 11</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn4"></a><a href="#_ednref4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Guardian, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">New primary school plans scrapped in Coventry after academies row</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, 16 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">October 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn5"></a><a href="#_ednref5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Guardian, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Why is God suddenly so big in the schools we all pay for?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, 26 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn6"></a><a href="#_ednref6">[vi]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> University of Lancaster, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">New poll reveals what people really think about faith schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, 19 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn7"></a><a href="#_ednref7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Guardian, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Michael Gove has washed his hands of planning for the future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, 23 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn8"></a><a href="#_ednref8">[viii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">National Pupil Projections: Future Trends in Pupil Numbers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, SFR11/2013, 21 March 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn9"></a><a href="#_ednref9">[ix]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Schools, Pupils and their Characteristics: January 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, SFR21/2013, 20 June 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn10"></a><a href="#_ednref10">[x]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> BBC, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">London council considers opening schools in split shifts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, BBC website, 4 September 2013</span></p></body></html>